{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517448"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:53:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:53:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12805"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.52,0.04,0.25,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89480"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5246"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73618"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49922"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89480"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman presents to the clinic with a 3-month history of joint pain affecting her wrists and ankles. The pain is worse in the morning and associated with stiffness of the joints that lasts a few hours. She denies any recent trauma or overuse. Additionally, she also complains of persistent fatigue which is unrelieved by rest and intermittent low-grade subjective fevers. There is no history of skin rashes, hair loss or mouth sores. Her past medical history is unremarkable except for frequent headaches.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, she appears tired but is not in acute distress. Her vital signs are all within normal limits. There is mild swelling and tenderness in her wrists and metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints, with reduced range of motion. The rest of the examination is unremarkable\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven her symptoms, the following laboratory tests were made:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete Blood Count:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnaemia (Haemoglobin 105 g/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeukopenia (WBC: 3.5 x 10^3/\u00b5L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythrocyte Sedimentation Rate (ESR): 45 mm/hr (elevated)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein (CRP): 30mg/L (elevated)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal function tests: Normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplement levels (C3, C4): Normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERheumatoid factor (RF): Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntinuclear antibody (ANA) test: Positive at a titer of 1:640 (homogeneous pattern)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-dsDNA antibodies: Positive, 40 IU/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplement levels (C3, C4): Normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis: Normal, no cells or casts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line management for the patients underlying cause of her presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ibuprofen","Hydroxychloroquine","Rituximab","Methotrexate","Leflunomide"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical presentation and laboratory findings, the patient is most likely suffering from systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), an autoimmune disease characterized by joint pain, fatigue, and systemic symptoms. The presence of symmetric inflammatory joint pain, fatigue, low-grade fevers, positive ANA and anti-dsDNA antibodies supports this diagnosis. Although rashes commonly occur in SLE, they may not always be present. Complement can be low in SLE in situations of internal organ involvement, especially lupus nephritis. However, complement is frequently normal especially with mild SLE manifestations.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EThe most appropriate management for SLE involves immunosuppression or immunomodulation. In this case, the most suitable option among the choices provided is \u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxychloroquine\u003C/strong\u003E. Hydroxychloroquine is an antirheumatic drug that is used to treat the manifestations of SLE. It is also the only agent with a demonstrated mortality benefit in SLE in addition to reducing the frequency of flares.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIbuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E is a Non-Steroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drug (NSAID) which is useful for managing joint pain and inflammation. However, it does not address the underlying autoimmune activity of SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERituximab\u003C/strong\u003E is a biologic agent that can be used to manage various autoimmune diseases, including rheumatoid arthritis and SLE, especially when conventional synthetic disease-modifying anti-rheumatic drug (DMARD) therapies have failed. Rituximab is not typically used as first-line treatment for mild to moderate joint symptoms, especially when there is no clinical evidence of serious organ involvement or refractory disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is a DMARD which is commonly prescribed for autoimmune conditions including rheumatoid arthritis, psoriasis, SLE and inflammatory bowel disease. However, while Methotrexate can be effective for managing joint symptoms in patients with SLE, it may not be required if hydroxychloroquine adequately treats the inflammatory joint disease. Therefore, Methotrexate is not the most appropriate first-line management for this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeflunomide\u003C/strong\u003E is another Disease-Modifying Antirheumatic Drug (DMARDs) that is commonly used in the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis. It works by inhibiting pyrimidine synthesis, thereby suppressing immune responses. It is more commonly used in rheumatoid arthritis and may be considered as an alternative or adjunctive therapy in cases of SLE where conventional treatments have failed or are not well tolerated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydroxychloroquine is first line management for SLE"],"references":["1.DeQuattro K, Trupin L, Murphy LB, Rush S, Criswell LA, Lanata CM, et al. High Disease Severity Among Asians in a US Multiethnic Cohort of Individuals with Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. Arthritis Care \u0026 Research. 2020 Dec 18;","\u200cAringer M, Costenbader K, Daikh D, et al: 2019 European League Against Rheumatism/American College of Rheumatology Classification Criteria for Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. Arthritis Rheumatol 71(9):1400\u20131412, 2019. doi: 10.1002/art.40930"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73618"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12805"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/73618"},"attributes":{"crea